🧩 Problem: Next Greater Element (NGE)

Given an array, for each element find:

first greater element on the right

🧠 1. Brute Force
💬 What you say

“For each element, I’ll scan to the right and find the first greater element.”

✅ Code (Brute)
int[] nextGreater(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length;
    int[] res = new int[n];

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        res[i] = -1; // default

        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if (nums[j] > nums[i]) {
                res[i] = nums[j];
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    return res;
}
⏱ Complexity
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)
❌ Problem

Repeated work — same elements checked multiple times

3. Optimal Approach (Monotonic Stack)
🧠 Key Idea

Use a stack to store indices of elements waiting for next greater

Algorithm (Right-to-Left Traversal):
Traverse the array from right to left.
For the current element, pop all elements from the stack that are smaller than or equal to it (they cannot be the NGE for any element to the left).
If the stack is not empty, the top of the stack is the NGE. If empty, the NGE is -1.
Push the current element onto the stack for future comparisons

----------------------------------------------------------
import java.util.Stack;

public class NextGreaterElement {
    public static int[] getNGE(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        int[] result = new int[n];
        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        // Traverse from right to left
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            // Remove smaller elements from stack
            while (!stack.isEmpty() && stack.peek() <= arr[i]) {
                stack.pop();
            }
            // If stack empty, no greater element on right
            result[i] = stack.isEmpty() ? -1 : stack.peek();
            
            // Push current element to stack
            stack.push(arr[i]);
        }
        return result;
    }
}
